### Example 16: Scale Factor Between Similar Triangles

If two triangles are similar, the ratio of corresponding sides is constant—the *scale factor*.

<!-- BUILD: Same two triangles; compute the three ratios of corresponding sides; confirm they are equal. -->

```scheme
(define T1-A (geom/point 0.0 0.0))
(define T1-B (geom/point 3.0 0.0))
(define T1-C (geom/point 0.0 4.0))

(define T2-A (geom/point 0.0 0.0))
(define T2-B (geom/point 6.0 0.0))
(define T2-C (geom/point 0.0 8.0))

(define T1-AB (geom/distance T1-A T1-B))
(define T1-BC (geom/distance T1-B T1-C))
(define T1-CA (geom/distance T1-C T1-A))

(define T2-AB (geom/distance T2-A T2-B))
(define T2-BC (geom/distance T2-B T2-C))
(define T2-CA (geom/distance T2-C T2-A))

(define k1 (/ T2-AB T1-AB))
(define k2 (/ T2-BC T1-BC))
(define k3 (/ T2-CA T1-CA))

(display \"Ratios of corresponding sides:\")
(newline)
(display \"AB: \")
(display k1)
(newline)
(display \"BC: \")
(display k2)
(newline)
(display \"CA: \")
(display k3)
(newline)
(display \"Scale factor: \")
(display k1)
(newline)
```

[VISUAL: The two triangles overlaid (one in blue, one in red), with corresponding sides labeled. The three ratios printed: all equal to 2.0.]

---

### Example 17: Indirect Measurement (Height of a Tree)

You stand 6 feet tall and cast a 4-foot shadow. At the same time a tree casts a 28-foot shadow. How tall is the tree?

The triangles (you + shadow, tree + shadow) are similar (same sun angle). So  
$$\\frac{\\text{tree height}}{\\text{tree shadow}} = \\frac{\\text{your height}}{\\text{your shadow}}.$$

<!-- BUILD: Diagram of two similar right triangles. Solve for tree height. -->

```scheme
(define your-height 6.0)
(define your-shadow 4.0)
(define tree-shadow 28.0)

(define tree-height (* your-height (/ tree-shadow your-shadow)))

(display \"Your height: \")
(display your-height)
(display \" ft, your shadow: \")
(display your-shadow)
(display \" ft\")
(newline)
(display \"Tree shadow: \")
(display tree-shadow)
(display \" ft\")
(newline)
(display \"Tree height: \")
(display tree-height)
(display \" ft\")
(newline)
```

[VISUAL: Two right triangles. Small triangle: vertical leg 6 (labeled \"you\"), horizontal leg 4 (shadow). Large triangle: vertical leg 42 (labeled \"tree\"), horizontal leg 28 (shadow). Hypotenuses represent sunlight. Caption \"Tree height = 42 ft\".]

---

### Example 18: Proportional Segments (Dividing a Segment)

If a line parallel to one side of a triangle intersects the other two sides, it divides those sides proportionally.

<!-- BUILD: Triangle ABC; a line parallel to BC intersects AB at D and AC at E. Measure AD/DB and AE/EC; confirm equal. -->

```scheme
(define A (geom/point 0.0 4.0))
(define B (geom/point 0.0 0.0))
(define C (geom/point 6.0 0.0))

;; Line parallel to BC at height y = 2 intersects AB and AC
;; AB is vertical from (0,0) to (0,4), so D is at (0,2)
(define D (geom/point 0.0 2.0))

;; AC goes from (0,4) to (6,0); at y=2, solve for x
;; slope of AC: (0-4)/(6-0) = -2/3; equation: y - 4 = (-2/3)(x - 0)
;; 2 - 4 = (-2/3)x => x = 3
(define E (geom/point 3.0 2.0))

(define AD (geom/distance A D))
(define DB (geom/distance D B))
(define AE (geom/distance A E))
(define EC (geom/distance E C))

(define ratio1 (/ AD DB))
(define ratio2 (/ AE EC))

(display \"AD = \")
(display AD)
(display \", DB = \")
(display DB)
(display \", ratio AD/DB = \")
(display ratio1)
(newline)
(display \"AE = \")
(display AE)
(display \", EC = \")
(display EC)
(display \", ratio AE/EC = \")
(display ratio2)
(newline)
(display \"Ratios equal? \")
(display (< (abs (- ratio1 ratio2)) 0.001))
(newline)
```

[VISUAL: Cartesian plane. Triangle ABC with A at (0,4), B at (0,0), C at (6,0). Horizontal line y = 2 drawn in red, intersecting AB at D (0,2) and AC at E (3,2). Segments AD, DB, AE, EC labeled. Caption \"AD/DB = AE/EC (proportional division)\".]

